				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>In Telling the Future, Op-Talk asks people from a variety of fields to speculate on what we have to look forward to â and what we should watch out for.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ayanna M. Howard helps robots become more like people. âWeâre not that efficient,â she says, âyet somehow we still survive.â In her research, Dr. Howard,Â the <a href="//robotics.gatech.edu/team/faculty/howard">Motorola Foundation professor</a> in the School of Electrical and Computer Engineering at Georgia Tech, asks: âWhat is it that allows us to still function? Can we grab some of that information and learn about that and provide it to robotics?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The idea of robots acting like people might be worrying for some. At The Washington Post, David Tuffley recently <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/01/05/in-10-years-the-job-market-will-look-totally-different-heres-how-to-make-sure-youre-ready/">considered</a> the prospect that robots would one day replace us at work: âAlmost any job that can be described as a âprocessâ could be done by a computer, whether that computer is housed in a robot or embedded somewhere out of sight.â (At The Billfold, Nicole Dieker <a href="//thebillfold.com/2015/01/how-to-make-sure-you-do-not-lose-your-job-to-a-robot/">suggests</a> that one way to avoid getting robo-replaced is to âbe the most amazing person ever.â) And at The Times, Robin Marantz Henig <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/01/11/magazine/death-by-robot.html">investigates</a> efforts to teach robots morals, so they can decide whether to use a weapon or how to behave in an impending crash. âMaybe we should be worried about outsourcing morality to robots as easily as weâve outsourced so many other forms of human labor,â Ms. Henig writes. âMaking hard questions easy should give us pause.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Dr. Howard says robotics shouldnât scare us: âAt the end of the day, the people who build robotics are people, and most of us actually do careÂ and understand that robots have to live in the same arena as people.â She talked to Op-Talk aboutÂ how robots could shape the future of health care, sports and disaster response â and even help Americans get jobs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What do you hope will be different in fiveÂ years?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">IÂ wish that we would have more of the things that we do in the robotics world, more of the research that weâre doing, integrated in society. Youâre actually starting to see that, even though people donât realize it. For example, cars that now do some automated parking â that came from robotics folks working on autonomous vehicles and things like that. IÂ want to see a lot of the cool stuff weâre still doing that people donât know about being in our little gadgets and our homes â me going into my house and knowing that my son just finished up the milk, and thereâs no milk in the refrigerator. Could it come up with a way where all of a sudden, I open up my door and thereâs this vehicle thatâs like, âHereâs your milk cartonâ? Maybe not at that level, but something in between that just makes life a lot easier.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Whatâs an example of the kind of cool stuff from the robotics field that you hopeÂ people know more about in the future?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One example would be dealing with haptic expressionÂ â in order for robotics to actually manipulate and grab things in the world in a robust fashion, they have to be able to feel things likeÂ textures and adapt in terms of their gripping. So that kind of technology, whereÂ youâre doing modeling and youâre adapting to the shape and the contour â a really simple example is, it would be really nice if I could get into my car and my car seat actually adapts to my back. We can do that, because itâs the same kind of actuation and molding, and yet people wouldnât realize this actually came from people in a robotics role having to do this in a different scenario.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What are you afraid will be different in fiveÂ years?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What Iâm afraid of is that society will start thinking that robotics is dangerous. Recently, for example, thereâs been this whole initiative on artificial intelligence â you know, âwe need to be careful.â I think that those forewarnings are way too early. We see it in science fiction, but we donât open up the papers and they say, âRobotics: we need to stop it now, because these robots are going to take over,â because weâre just not there. But in five years, as we start seeing these technologies come out, I think weâre going start getting these questions, and so thatâs my fear, that those questions are going to come upÂ before weâre at the stage where they really need to, and that might stop the development.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Thereâs a lot of debate now over whether robots are going to take our jobs in the future. Is that something you think about?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I used to. But really, that question is not, âAre robots going to take our jobs?â Itâs, âIs technology going to take our jobs?â It has nothing to do with robotics, it just has to do with the fact that as a society we build technology to make our lives better and more efficient, so from the Industrial Revolution days, you could say the same thing. And so itâs not, âAre robots going to take our jobs?â I think that the inclusion of robots in our society changes the nature of the jobs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong> What issue or event that weâre talking about now will be completely forgotten in fiveÂ years?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I think the issue of jobs will change. Right nowÂ thereâs this whole thing of weÂ donât have enough jobs, even though weâre seeing the economyâs a little better, thereâs more job creation. Iâm hoping that as robotics allowsÂ more jobs to come on shore, that weÂ wonât have these discussions five years from now.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The other issue I hopeÂ isnât there is this whole issue of not having enough representation in theÂ major technology companies. If you look at the number of women that areÂ hired, itâs not representative of the United States. Hopefully that wonât be in the news five years from now.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What issue or event will we still remember?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Weâll still be talking about health care, terrorism and war. I think as long as people are here weâre going to have that.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>So you donât think the health care debate weâre having now is going toÂ resolved in fiveÂ years?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No,Â IâmÂ pretty sure itâs not. We have to wait for the nextÂ presidency, and then if any changes are made it still takes time, and then add fiveÂ years to whenever a decision is made. Iâm very hopeful, though, thatÂ thereâs been a lot of changes in health care which have been good, which has actually been good for technologists. What happens is because the health care systemÂ has to change, youâre starting to see a lot of the hospitals and the clinics starting to adopt technology much more than they were. Itâs like, âif we provide a system where they can take it home, and it helps them monitor their diabetes or something, guess what? TheyÂ donât come back to us.â Which I think might even change the question again about health care in fiveÂ years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What kind of technologies do you see being adopted?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Really itâs about the in-home technologies. WhenÂ youâre released from a hospital or clinic, typically youâre given instructions on a piece of paper, and youâre really expected to remember whatâs on the piece of paper â but instead, giving things like a mini robot coach, or a suite of mobile apps that the clinician or the doctor actually programs for you, and you just basically have to put it on your hip, so it beeps and you look at it and it shows you howÂ youâre supposed to do your exercises, or your therapy, or shows you a little picture of the pill youâre supposed to take. Those kinds of things, in terms of technology, theyâre not revolutionary, but them being designed so that theyâre useful to the general public, thatâs really where the innovation is.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>And how do you think those technologies might change the conversation around health care?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">IÂ truly believe thatÂ whatÂ youâre going to start seeing, when itâs shown that these areÂ effective, that if you give someone a very simple âx,â whether itâs a mobile app or a little robot, guess what? It reduces theirÂ return to the hospital by 60 percent. Right now these technologies are notÂ reimbursable necessarily, so now itâs like, âHey, maybe we should make these reimbursable, because it actually increases our bottom line.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">AÂ big thing that weâre working on at a lot of universities is telemedicine. If I have a doctor, say, in Atlanta, and we have a lot of rural areas outside, how do you get care to someone whoâs 200 miles from Atlanta? If there was a clinic there that maybe doesnât have the expertise, but you can go there andÂ get diagnosed, and have a haptic robot feel for palpitations and things like that â right now though, that kind of system is not reimbursable.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Who or what in your fieldÂ will people be talking about a lot more in fiveÂ years?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Youâre starting to hear the conversation now, and itâs about exoskeletons. In fact, thereâs a bunch of start-ups now that are pushing forward exoskeletons and things like that. Thereâs an <a href="//www.cybathlon.ethz.ch/">Olympics</a> now for people who have robotic parts. I think thatâs going to open up a wide world.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Will we see exoskeletons to help people with disabilities, or for other applications, too?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">IÂ think whatâs going to happen, just like a lot of technologies for individuals with disabilities, it starts out with disabilities, and then it evolves. It could be that itâs an exoskeleton for a doctor who has to go into a Hurricane Katrina kind of thing, where functionally a person with a disability can use it but the benefits of it are so great thatÂ itâs adopted by other people.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>This interview has been condensed and edited.</em></p>
